# Code quality

Follow these expectations when writing or changing code. Adapt idioms to the language and stack in use.

## Security
- Validate and sanitize input at trust boundaries; prefer allowlists.
- Parameterize queries and commands; never concatenate untrusted input into SQL, shell, or OS calls.
- Do not commit secrets; use environment variables or your org’s secret store.
- Avoid exposing stack traces, internal paths, or sensitive data to end users.

## Structure and clarity
- Match existing patterns in the repo (layout, naming, error handling) before introducing new styles.
- Keep modules focused; prefer small, composable units over large tangled files.
- Make data flow and control flow easy to follow at boundaries (APIs, FFI, config loading).

## Types, contracts, and invariants
- Where the language supports it, use types, interfaces, or schemas to document boundaries and catch mistakes early.
- Be explicit about preconditions, postconditions, and failure modes for non-trivial operations.
- Prefer immutable or narrowly mutable data where it reduces bugs, per language norms.

## Testing and docs
- Add or update tests when the repo has a test setup and behavior changes.
- Document public surfaces, non-obvious behavior, and anything future maintainers must not break.
- When the **Testing** plugin is installed, it owns the test-writing and test-execution workflows; this rule only sets the baseline expectation that changed behavior should be covered.
- When the **Technical Writing** plugin is installed, it owns README hygiene and long-form developer-facing docs; this rule only sets the baseline expectation to document important behavior.
